   "hider_text": "The curve of a backrest pressed against the small of your spine.  \nCold maple in the morning, like breath held too long.  \nA shadow pulled tight at the edge of the floorboard — not a shadow, but a hollow where something used to stand.  \nThe way dust settles in the corners when no one is looking — not just dust, but silence that has a shape.  \nYou / The metal rail groans under the weight of a child’s foot, not the one that should be there. The air hums with the kind of quiet that only comes after rain has passed and the sky forgets how to hold its breath. A patch of grass, stiff and cracked, holds the shape of a shadow — not a person, not a car, just something that once moved with rhythm / The wind moves through the valley like breath between stones. It doesn’t carry sound, just pressure — a slow pull that shifts the dust from one slope to the next. You can feel it in the hollows of your ribs, the way it makes your skin tingle, not with cold, but with absence.  \n\nThere’s a line where the earth turns from cracked to grey, like a photograph",
   "seeker_text": "The color of the first light that wakes me up in the dark.  \nNot the sun. Not the lamp.  \nThe one that spills through the crack in the curtain, just before I open my eyes — a thin, pale gold, like a suggestion of honey poured over winter glass.  \nI remember the way it pooled on the floor, not bright, not harsh, but alive — a quiet / The scent of wet earth after rain.  \nNot the sharp, clean smell of a garden hose, not the chemical tang of pavement.  \nThis is the deep, slow breath of soil—ancient and quiet—after the first drops have soaked through.  \nIt rises from the ground in a soft, green hum, like the world is exhaling.  \nI stand barefoot on the edge of / The smell of wet earth after rain.  \n\nNot the kind that comes after a storm, but the kind that settles in the early morning, when the air still holds the breath of night. It’s not sharp or sudden—just deep, slow, like the world is breathing again. I remember standing barefoot on the back step of my grandmother’s house, the wood cool and damp under my toes"
  },
  {
   "round": 0,
   "hider_text": "The salt hangs in the air like dust from a forgotten door.  \nIt settles on the back of the throat when you breathe too deep, sharp and thin, like a shard of glass held just beneath the skin.  \n\nThere’s a shape in the corner of the room — not a thing, not quite — a curve that moves when the light shifts. It doesn’t belong to walls or shadows.",
   "seeker_text": "The scent of old paper in the attic—dusty, sun-bleached, the kind that makes your skin prickle like static. Not the sharp tang of ink, but the slow breath of time curled into folds. One corner of a yellowed ledger is curled like a sleeping cat. I touched it. Nothing happened. But for a second, I *felt* the weight of a hand",
